review:
I can remember how excited I was to get SC4 Deluxe back when it first came out ...
(and I actually did get a good laugh out of 'warped regions' - the improper bit-map config files that appeared to create overlapping cities)
--- and I actually had years of play time with this game, before it came to Steam ---
--- not to mention the oversized plug-in folder, now on it's very own usb drive ---

... now it is available on Steam!

A few pet peeves with this one:[list]
[*] The SC4 terraforming tools were the new 'area effect' ones, NOT an improvement in my opinion (as an 'addition to' would have been nifty - yes, but as a 'complete replacement' ... there were times I would have liked to have the old tile-by-tile tools ... - no);
[*] Due to the dev's not understanding that elevated (already having a 'bridge' structure) transit doesn't need to use a BRIDGE to cross 'ground/surface water' (thus creating visual issues resulting from requiring a bridge to cross ANY water (in previous versions of SimCity) neither 'ground/surface water' nor hydroelectric power plants were available in SC4;
[*] The near impossible requirements to get a bridge that didn't have water somewhere below it;
[*] The way bridges were implemented didn't allow for above ground transit crossing underneath one - regardless of how much difference in elevation there might be;
[*] And Electronic Arts only officially released one (of several possible) expansion packages.[/list]
The (imo) noteworthy redeeming features include:[list]
[*] The ability for water craft (ferries, freight and leisure) to make it under a sufficiently high bridge;
[*] The stubs, in a neighbor city, that an intercity connection made - of whatever ... transit, utility, etc ... you chose to establish.
[*] The (new - for that time) 'modding' tools;
[*] As I remember it, the first SimCity to have a 64-bit version;
[*] And the bump up in available map sizes (64x64, 128x128, and -NEW- 256x256).[/list]
All said - IMO - the best city simulater I have seen.
